    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-04-01T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-04-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="483"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d483">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 702.6811/44.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <persName type="from">Attorney</persName> General to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of Justice</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-04-01">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 1, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to say that, as requested in
                    your letter of the 28th ultimo, the Department has instructed the United States
                    Attorney at Philadelphia to call the attention of the judge of the United States
                    District Court for the Eastern District of Pennsylvania to the provisions of
                    Article VI of the Convention of July 11, 1903,<note n="3" xml:id="d483fn3">Date
                        of proclamation of the Consular Convention of Nov. 19, 1902.</note> with
                    Greece (33 Stats. 2126), guaranteeing the inviolability of consular offices, and
                    to suggest the apparent advisability of the dissolution of the order enjoining
                    the Greek Consul at Philadelphia to hold certain papers transmitted to him by
                    the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, pending the further direction of the Court.</p>
                <closer>For the Attorney General: <lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">E. Marvin Underwood</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
